So is this just to reduce verbosity? If so I do wonder if it should be called awaitAct or some-such, as it would appear to have no direct knowledge of anything to do with search.
But also, what's the net gain here? The removal of one use of the async and await keywords? If so, maybe it's not needed, but let me throw in an example for our consideration:
    await updateSearchOptions(() => {
      input.simulate("change", { target: { value: "new query" } });
      jest.advanceTimersByTime(1000);
    });
Is this simply the same as:
    await act( async () => {
      input.simulate("change", { target: { value: "new query" } });
      await jest.advanceTimersByTime(1000);
    });
?

